prompt:
Review and repair this Python 3 worker pool:

class Pool:
    def __init__(self, n):
        self.q = queue.Queue()
        self.stop = False
        self.threads = [threading.Thread(target=self.worker) for _ in range(n)]
        for t in self.threads: t.start()
    def worker(self):
        while not self.stop:
            fn = self.q.get()
            fn()
            self.q.task_done()
    def submit(self, fn): self.q.put(fn)
    def shutdown(self):
        self.stop = True
        self.q.join()
        for t in self.threads: t.join()

Requirements: identify all shutdown/deadlock/task-accounting problems; implement a thread-safe pool with graceful shutdown that finishes accepted tasks; reject submissions once shutdown begins; survive task exceptions; make shutdown idempotent; define behavior for n <= 0 and shutdown called from a worker. Use only the standard library. Include tests for the critical races. Keep the answer under 1500 words.
